    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>There are new methods added to <code>java.util.Arrays</code> to convert an array into a Java 8 stream which can then be used for summing etc.</p>\n<pre><code>int sum =  Arrays.stream(myIntArray).sum();\n</code></pre>\n<p>Multiplying two arrays is a little more difficult because I can't think of a way to get the value AND the index at the same time as a Stream operation. This means you probably have to stream over the indexes of the array.</p>\n<pre><code>//in this example a[] and b[] are same length\nint[] a = ...\nint[] b = ...\n \nint[] result = new int[a.length];\n\nIntStream.range(0, a.length).forEach(i -&gt; result[i] = a[i] * b[i]);\n</code></pre>\n<hr />\n<p>Commenter <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/2711488/holger\">@Holger</a> points out you can use the <code>map</code> method instead of <code>forEach</code> like this:</p>\n<pre><code>int[] result = IntStream.range(0, a.length).map(i -&gt; a[i] * b[i]).toArray();\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1649804,
      "reputation" : 2516,
      "user_id" : 1520617,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8cc19e06b32f1cc6e6e3aadfb8d7d43b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Ian Knight",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1520617/ian-knight"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 63,
    "last_activity_date" : 1403629733,
    "last_edit_date" : 1403629733,
    "creation_date" : 1403625986,
    "answer_id" : 24391402,
    "question_id" : 24390463,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can turn an array into a stream by using <code>Arrays.stream()</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int[] ns = new int[] {1,2,3,4,5};\nArrays.stream(ns);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Once you've got your stream, you can use any of the methods described in <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Stream.html\">the documentation</a>, like <code>sum()</code> or whatever. You can <code>map</code> or <code>filter</code> like in Python by calling the relevant stream methods with a Lambda function:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Arrays.stream(ns).map(n -&gt; n * 2);\nArrays.stream(ns).filter(n -&gt; n % 4 == 0);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Once you're done modifying your stream, you then call <code>toArray()</code> to convert it back into an array to use elsewhere:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int[] ns = new int[] {1,2,3,4,5};\nint[] ms = Arrays.stream(ns).map(n -&gt; n * 2).filter(n -&gt; n % 4 == 0).toArray();\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 248909,
      "reputation" : 23380,
      "user_id" : 524588,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 78,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ea4fe82eb145cb38c19e4c83389f4fe?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Sanghyun Lee",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/524588/sanghyun-lee"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 11,
    "last_activity_date" : 1463817855,
    "creation_date" : 1463817855,
    "answer_id" : 37360435,
    "question_id" : 24390463,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Be careful if you have to deal with large numbers.</p>\n\n<pre><code>int[] arr = new int[]{Integer.MIN_VALUE, Integer.MIN_VALUE};\nlong sum = Arrays.stream(arr).sum(); // Wrong: sum == 0\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The sum above is not <code>2 * Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>.\nYou need to do this in this case.</p>\n\n<pre><code>long sum = Arrays.stream(arr).mapToLong(Long::valueOf).sum(); // Correct\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1313740,
      "reputation" : 2736,
      "user_id" : 1261162,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 60,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/1PwKU.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Rafael",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1261162/rafael"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1509352522,
    "creation_date" : 1509352522,
    "answer_id" : 47010883,
    "question_id" : 24390463,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Please note that Arrays.stream(arr) create a LongStream (or IntStream, ...) instead of Stream so the map function cannot be used to modify the type. This is why .mapToLong, mapToObject, ... functions are provided.</p>\n\n<p>Take a look at <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29028980/why-cant-i-map-integers-to-strings-when-streaming-from-an-array\">why-cant-i-map-integers-to-strings-when-streaming-from-an-array</a></p>\n"
  } ],
